[2] France: economical aspects
Date: Thu 11 Dec 2008
Source: Proceedings, INRA's (French National Institute for
Agricultural Research) 15th '3R days' (Research in Ruminants), Paris,
3-4 Dec 2008 (in French, trans. & abridged Rapp.SB, edited]
<http://www.web-agri.fr/dossier_special/default.asp?idDoss=110&idrub=2080&id=52169>


The economical impact of BTV-8 on French cattle and sheep
---------------------------------------------------------
[For the names of the authors, go to the URL above]

The consequences of the bluetongue are measurable in all fields of
study, with deaths up to 25 percent in sheep, up to 13 percent in
suckling cattle [that is, beef cows with calves at foot. - Rapp.SB],
and 16 percent in dairy cows.

For the 1st time, a techno-economic study of the consequences of
bluetongue disease evaluates that there is between 6 and 18 percent
reduction of gross profit margin in farms with suckling cattle and
between 1 and 8 percent decline in dairy farming. In critical cases,
the losses will be up to 43 percent in suckling livestock and 12
percent in dairy cattle.

The crisis has had, and will continue to have, a major impact in
cattle. The direct impacts concern the production and/or marketing,
but the indirect effects by decreased fertility will be just as
damaging. The drop in fertility is already being felt: lower success
rates in IA [artificial insemination], more abortions. "These details
make us fear a major impact of the bluetongue [disease] on
reproduction, with possible medium term repercussions with shortage
of animals due to abortions, or lengthening the intercalving periods.

The estimated direct effects on milk production were studied in the
Picardy (region of northeastern France. - Rapp.SB), where 10 percent
reduction was seen in cows ill for 3 weeks. The losses are rather
difficult to assess in the beef sector, but the data indicate a 23
percent decrease in export volume. Weight gain is affected; there are
direct impacts on prices and the effects on the entire industry are
already visible. Workload is increased by an average of 1.5 hour
daily [per holding].

[Byline: Nathalie Petit]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Susan Baekeland

